instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The incubator Digital Twin follows a lifecycle composed of (1) a development phase where the physical hardware (styrofoam box, heat‑bed, fan, temperature sensors) and the software stack (Raspberry Pi controller, low‑level driver, RabbitMQ communication server) are defined (Document 2, 5); (2) a modelling phase in which two simulation models (Model A and Model B) are constructed based on the four assumptions (Document 6); (3) a calibration phase that runs the calibration algorithm (section 3.3) to estimate model parameters from sensor data (Document 1, 4); (4) an operation phase where data from the physical twin are continuously streamed to the DT, monitors evaluate safety and performance, and visualization dashboards display the current status (Document 1, 4); and (5) a self‑adaptation phase that closes the loop by detecting anomalies, planning experiments, re‑calibrating the model, updating the Kalman filter and the controller, and re‑deploying new control parameters (Document 4). Transition between phases is managed through the RabbitMQ communication infrastructure and the calibration/monitoring algorithms, providing governance of the DT throughout its life."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity relies on four explicit assumptions: (1) uniform temperature distribution inside the box (ensured by the fan), (2) negligible heat storage in the box walls, (3) constant specific heat capacity of the internal air, and (4) that the majority of electrical power is converted to heat in the air (relaxed in Model B). Validation is performed by experimental comparison of model predictions against measured temperature traces (section 4 of the study, not detailed here) and by calibrating model parameters on‑line. Uncertainty sources include sensor noise, the simplifying assumptions above, and errors in estimated parameters. On‑demand calibration and a Kalman filter‑based state estimator are used to detect anomalies, re‑estimate the heatbed temperature, and correct model drift, thereby providing a quality‑assurance loop for the Digital Twin."
]

